title: A systematic study of elastic scattering of polarized deuterons around 30 MeV by complex nuclei

x4freetext: A systematic study of elastic scattering of polarized
deuterons around 30 MeV by complex nuclei

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.282, p.221 (1977)

x4freetext: The beam polarization is monitored in a carbon
polarimeter sitting in a small (40 cm diam.) chamber
placed downstream behind the 65 cm scattering chamber.
The target is a strip of 9 mg/cm2 polyethylene (CH2)n
foil 3 mm wide and 60 mm high held in a 60 mm diameter
target holder wide enough not to disturb the
Faraday cup measurement.
The detectors are conventional Si(Li) detectors set
at angles +-45 degr. symmetric to the beam.
The absolute normalization of the l2C polarimeter has
been done in a separate run by comparison with
accurate d+4He data at 15 MeV (R. A. Hardekopf,etc.
LASL Report LA-5051,1972) and then checked against the
data on 4H4 and 12C (J. Arvieux,etc. Nucl.Inst.,
The detectors are mounted onto two
arms which rotate around the target. Each telescope is
made up of a thin (200 to 500 mu-m) surface-barrier
dE detector followed by a thick (3 or 4 mm) Si(Li)
drift E-detector.
In a few measurements (58Ni,64Zn,ll8Sn,120Sn)
instead of a E-dE telescope were used a single 3 mm
E-detector.
The beam intensity is monitored twice. A
relative normalization is given by a thick Si(Li)
detector held at a fixed angle of 45 degr. The absolute
normalization is measured with a Faraday cup placed at
the end of the beam line.
